<p>&quot;Oh my <em>King</em>, is your girlfriend always that violent?&quot;</p>
<p>Isabella blinked; the indigo fog that enveloped everything around her was still there.</p>
<p>The&#8230; demon? The demon sighed. &quot;Right, right, forgot y'all can't look into the localized time business. Well, long story short, your girlfriend just threatened me with a broken bottle.&quot; It held its hands out. &quot;I ain't even do anything! I mean, sure, I looked into her mind and all, but don't a broker got a right to know what the client wants?&quot;</p>
<p>This was exactly the sort of nonsense being associated with Cousin Bradley engendered. Isabella wouldn't be questioning too much of it.</p>
<p>&quot;So&#8230;&quot; The demon mimed a thinking pose. &quot;You look like you know what to wish for. Do gotta warn you, I'm the 'equivalent exchange' kinda wish-granter. Don't worry, your immortal soul's not on the menu. Less valuable than you'd think.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Was that&#8230; supposed to be an insult?&quot; Isabella shifted in place, and realized that the shadow of Veronica weighed a lot less in the indigo fogscape.</p>
<p>&quot;Not at all, little Bella! Human souls, too much upkeep, not much return. Costs a fortune to keep 'em outta Gehenna. And by the way, that labcoat looks <em>dashing</em> with the hawaiian shirt.&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Wait, so the afterlife-&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;So!&quot; The demon snapped, and reclined into the fog. &quot;I got several offers on the table, if you're willlin'. Let's start with, and keep in mind hearin' your desires is gonna get a little weird, <em>Looking Glass To Eye</em><sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-3" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-3')">3</a></sup>.&quot;</p>
<p>Isabella wasn't sure whether to be angry at the mere mention of that debacle, or impressed that the demon had found a way to add footnotes to its speech.</p>
<p>&quot;Now, lookin' into your thoughts I'm torn whether this one concerns the art or the artist.&quot; The demon mimed contemplation from its foggy perch. &quot;That was <em>your</em> work, weren't it? Let me be the first to say that I'm sorry, sister; you deserved better. But: how do we define&#8230; 'better'?&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;Thank you?&quot; Regardless of the circumstances, it felt nice to <em>finally</em> be credited for her work. &quot;Is this about revenge, or attribution?&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;I'm willin' and ready to make you or break Alex. You want credit, I can give you credit. You want the piece to break out and beat Alex to creamed corn? I can get that.&quot; The demon snapped its fingers, and two contracts appeared out of the fog. &quot;Former's gonna cost you a <em>lot</em> less, but it's still gonna cost y'all.&quot;</p>
<p>Isabella furrowed her brow. &quot;How much, and will I be able to look over the contract before signing?&quot;</p>
<p>If the demon had eyes, it just rolled them. &quot;Of <em>course</em>, of course. What good do I do scammin' the Ambassador's VIPs?&quot; Apparently it had a throat, because it just cleared it. &quot;Now, if ya' want revenge, I'm gonna ask for&#8230; about three and a half years of your bass skills. Only fair you wipe off the time spent with Hydrocide.&quot;</p>
<p>Unacceptable. &quot;Unacceptable.&quot;</p>
<p>The contract to Isabella's right disappeared into smoke. &quot;That leaves credit. For that&#8230; I'm gonna ask for a song.&quot;</p>
<p>Isabella quirked an eyebrow. &quot;In the figurative sense?&quot;</p>
<p>&quot;No, I mean I'll commission a literal, actual song from y'all. Somethin' to get the dance floors of Alagadda pumpin'. Payment on completion. Sound good?&quot;</p>
<p>Isabella looked back to the contract on her left.</p>
